\section{Study IV: Reasoning Capabilities and Test-Time Scaling}
\label{sec:study4}

While Studies I through III established the efficiency and throughput advantages of the SDAR paradigm, a critical question remains: does the shift from autoregressive to blockwise diffusion capabilities alter the model's reasoning trajectory?
In this final study, we investigate the qualitative impact of SDAR on complex reasoning. We hypothesize that SDAR offers two distinct advantages beyond speed:
(1) **Relaxed Inductive Bias:** The local bidirectional attention within blocks allows the model to model non-causal structures (e.g., molecular formulas) better than strictly causal AR models.
(2) **Test-Time Scaling Synergy:** The high throughput demonstrated in Section~\ref{sec:study3} makes computation-heavy inference strategies, such as majority voting and pass@k, practically viable.

\begin{tcolorbox}[takeawaysbox]
\textbf{Key Findings:}
(1) \textbf{Reasoning Preservation:} SDAR adaptation retains long-context Chain-of-Thought (CoT) capabilities from strong AR backbones.
(2) \textbf{Scientific Domain Advantage:} The blockwise bidirectional attention provides a "free" domain adaptation benefit, significantly outperforming AR on tasks requiring local non-causal modeling (e.g., Chemistry).
(3) \textbf{Inference-Time Synergy:} SDAR's throughput advantage translates directly into reasoning gains, enabling massive test-time scaling (pass@k) that outperforms the computational budget-matched AR baseline.
\end{tcolorbox}

\subsection{Experimental Setup}

\paragraph{Training Methodology.}
To isolate the impact of the generative paradigm, we construct a controlled "Scientific Reasoning" suite. We utilize \textbf{Qwen3-30B-A3B} as the base.
\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Science-Aware Backbone (AR):} We first continually pre-train the base model on 1T tokens of scientific corpus (500B general science + 500B annealing) using the standard AR objective. This yields our intermediate checkpoint.
    \item \textbf{Paradigm Bifurcation:} From this checkpoint, we branch into two models:
    \begin{itemize}
        \item \textbf{AR-Baseline:} Continued training on 50B tokens using the AR objective.
        \item \textbf{SDAR-Model:} Converted and trained on the same 50B tokens using the blockwise diffusion objective.
    \end{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Instruction Tuning:} Both models undergo identical Supervised Fine-Tuning (SFT) on 0.5B high-quality long-CoT reasoning data.
\end{enumerate}
This ensures that any performance divergence is strictly attributable to the decoding paradigm (AR vs.\ SDAR) rather than data exposure.

\paragraph{Evaluation Protocol.}
We evaluate on a suite of frontier benchmarks:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{General Reasoning:} MMLU-Pro, GPQA-diamond.
    \item \textbf{Mathematics:} AIME-24/25, LiveMathBench-Hard (LMB-Hard).
    \item \textbf{Science \& Code:} Chembench, PHYSICS, ProteinLMBench, LiveCodeBench (LCB).
\end{itemize}
\textbf{Inference Configurations:}
The AR baseline uses standard sampling ($T=0.6, p=0.95$). The SDAR model uses static decoding with block size $B=4$.
For \textbf{Test-Time Scaling}, we generate $N$ reasoning paths ($N=8$ for GPQA; $N=32$ for Math) and report \textbf{Majority Vote} and \textbf{pass@k}.

\subsection{Paradigm Shift: Impact on Scientific Reasoning}
\label{partiii_results}

We first examine the intrinsic capability of the models under standard 1-sample decoding.

\paragraph{SDAR mitigates Causal Masking Bias.}
As shown in Table~\ref{tab:ar_vs_sdar_science}, SDAR matches the AR baseline on general physics and biology tasks but achieves dramatic gains on \textbf{ChemBench (+12.3\%)} and \textbf{GPQA-diamond (+5.5\%)}.
We attribute this to the \textit{blockwise bidirectional attention} inherent to SDAR.
Scientific data, such as SMILES strings in chemistry or complex equations, often contains local bidirectional dependencies that strictly causal AR models struggle to capture efficiently. SDAR relaxes this constraint within the decoding block, allowing the model to attend to future tokens within the local window during generation. This result suggests SDAR is not merely a "faster" AR, but a superior inductive bias for structured scientific data.

